The number of motorcyclists dying on Arizona roads has dramatically increased in the past five years in part because new riders and veterans who haven't ridden for years are hitting the streets without proper training.
Experts still say helmets are vital, but today they're just as likely to point to the type of people taking up riding to explain the increase in accidents.
More than 3,900 people died on motorcycles in the United States in 2004, up 7.3 % from the year before, according to preliminary highway safety numbers released Thursday by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
